Recall the definition of the Taylor polynomial. As an example, the 4th
degree Taylor polynomial of $f(x)$, centered around \emph{a} = 0,
is given by

\begin{align*}
f(x) \approx T_4(x) = f(0) + f'(0)x + f''(0)\frac{x^2}2 + f'''(0)\frac{x^3}{3!} + f''''(0)\frac{x^4}{4!}
\end{align*}

So we need to calculate a couple derivatives of \emph{cos(x)}.

We calculate the 4th order Taylor polynomial of $f(x)$, centered
around \emph{a = 0}.

\begin{align*}
f(x) &= \cos(x) \quad & f(0) &= 1\\
f'(x) &= -\sin(x) \quad & f'(0) &= 0 \\
f''(x) &= -\cos(x) \quad & f''(0) &= -1 \\
f'''(x) &= \sin(x) \quad & f'''(0) &= 0 \\
f''''(x) &= \cos(x) \quad & f''''(0) &= 1
\end{align*}

Therefore, \emph{T}\textsubscript{4}(\emph{x}) is given by

\begin{align*}
T_4(x) = 1 - \frac{x^{2}}{2} +\frac{x^{4}}{24}
\end{align*}
